<h1>CHAPTER 1: INTRODUCTION</h1>
<br/>
<h2>1.1 Background of the Project</h2>
<p>
  In the modern digital age, online recruitment has completely replaced conventional newspaper advertisements and manual CV submissions. Employment portals serve as a core link between prospective job seekers and recruiting organizations. A highly responsive web portal enables companies to advertise job roles globally and screen candidate responses efficiently. For job seekers, online portals simplify the process of browsing open roles, filtering roles by category/location, and submitting application credentials.
</p>
<p>
  However, many current job boards fail to balance rich information sets with visual design aesthetics, resulting in visual fatigue and high cognitive load. CareerHub is developed to address this visual gap by utilizing modern Single Page Application (SPA) technologies combined with responsive grids and consistent dark-mode styling variables.
</p>
<h2>1.2 Problem Statement</h2>
<p>
  Traditional online job application platforms suffer from three major issues:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Contrast Glare and Eye Strain</span>: Recruiters and job seekers spend hours looking at white screens, causing eye strain. The lack of standard, synchronized light and dark themes results in severe contrast discrepancies.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Layout Whitespace Mismatch</span>: Many pages feature horizontal whitespace gaps or alignment bugs (e.g., split white/dark backdrops on Post Job forms), making them look unpolished and unprofessional.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Poor Mobile Responsiveness</span>: Tables and forms frequently overflow margins on smaller devices, preventing candidates from applying or recruiters from reviewing portfolios on mobile screens.
  </li>
</ol>
<h2>1.3 Objectives</h2>
<p>
  The main objectives of this individual programming project are:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>To design and develop a fully functional, MERN-stack web portal named CareerHub.</li>
  <li>To implement a synchronized light/dark theme system that stores state persistently in local browser memory.</li>
  <li>To polish dashboard layouts, tables, and form inputs so they are visually aligned and display correct contrasts project-wide.</li>
  <li>To develop a dedicated recruiting overview panel where employers can check applicant details, update states, and view resume links side-by-side.</li>
  <li>To verify system reliability through comprehensive black-box and integration test plans.</li>
</ul>
<h2>1.4 Scope of the Project</h2>
<p>
  The scope of CareerHub is defined under three primary user modules:
</p>
<ol>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Job Seeker Module</span>: Registration/Login, account profile management, CV upload, active job searches with filtering (Location, Salary, Category), and job application tracking.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Recruiter/Employer Module</span>: Creating/Editing company profile details, posting job requirements, updating active job listing statuses (Active/Closed), and checking candidate applicants.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>System Admin Module</span>: Centralized platform statistics monitoring (Total users, active jobs, employer listings), user blocking/unblocking access, and job list management.
  </li>
</ol>
<h2>1.5 Limitations</h2>
<p>
  The current implementation has the following limitations:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>No active payment gateways are integrated for premium job postings.</li>
  <li>The email notification system uses nodemailer for testing and does not connect to an enterprise SMTP email distribution server.</li>
  <li>The candidate matching score relies on keywords and does not run deep NLP-based AI semantic parser matching.</li>
</ul>
<div class='page-break'></div>
<h1>CHAPTER 2: LITERATURE REVIEW</h1>
<br/>
<h2>2.1 Existing Systems or Similar Applications</h2>
<p>
  Online recruitment is dominated by large-scale commercial platforms:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>LinkedIn</span>: Excellent for social networking and corporate outreach, but features high visual clutter, distracting feeds, and complex premium payment structures.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Indeed</span>: Large database of listings, but uses a basic, flat design layout that feels dated and lacks responsive dark mode overlays on tables.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Glassdoor</span>: Focuses on employer reviews, but restricts listing visibility behind registration walls and features complex dashboard workflows.
  </li>
</ul>
<h2>2.2 Technologies Used in the Industry</h2>
<p>
  Modern job portals use a variety of frameworks to build scalable systems:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>React.js</span>: Used for building SPAs with component reusability and fast Virtual DOM updates.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Tailwind CSS</span>: A utility-first CSS framework that compiles clean styling utilities, enabling rapid layout adjustments.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Node.js & Express.js</span>: Provide lightweight runtime and routing engines to handle stateless REST APIs.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>MongoDB</span>: A NoSQL document database ideal for storing heterogeneous JSON-like user profiles and application histories.
  </li>
</ul>
<h2>2.3 Comparison of Existing Solutions</h2>
<p>
  The table below compares commercial platforms and the CareerHub project:
</p>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Feature</th>
      <th>LinkedIn</th>
      <th>Indeed</th>
      <th>CareerHub (This Project)</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td class='bold'>System Architecture</td>
      <td>Microservices (Java/Scala)</td>
      <td>Monolithic/SOA mix</td>
      <td>Single Page MERN Architecture</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class='bold'>Synchronized Dark Mode</td>
      <td>Partial (App only)</td>
      <td>None (Light only)</td>
      <td>Yes (System-wide localStorage theme)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class='bold'>Visual Layout Contrast</td>
      <td>Moderate Clutter</td>
      <td>Low/Dated Text layout</td>
      <td>High (Premium cards & custom scrolls)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class='bold'>Recruiting Panels</td>
      <td>Paid (Recruiter Lite)</td>
      <td>Basic Table List</td>
      <td>Yes (Included side-by-side candidates review)</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<div class='page-break'></div>
<h1>CHAPTER 3: SYSTEM ANALYSIS (SRS)</h1>
<br/>
<h2>3.1 Functional Requirements</h2>
<p>
  The system requirements are categorized by user role:
</p>
<h3>3.1.1 Job Seeker Module</h3>
<ul>
  <li><span class='bold'>FR-JS-1</span>: The system shall allow seekers to register and login securely.</li>
  <li><span class='bold'>FR-JS-2</span>: The system shall enable seekers to search for jobs by title, category, and location.</li>
  <li><span class='bold'>FR-JS-3</span>: The system shall enable seekers to upload a PDF resume.</li>
  <li><span class='bold'>FR-JS-4</span>: The system shall allow seekers to toggle light/dark modes.</li>
</ul>
<h3>3.1.2 Recruiter/Employer Module</h3>
<ul>
  <li><span class='bold'>FR-RC-1</span>: The system shall allow employers to post new jobs with salary, location, and description.</li>
  <li><span class='bold'>FR-RC-2</span>: The system shall enable employers to toggle job listing states (Active/Closed).</li>
  <li><span class='bold'>FR-RC-3</span>: The system shall display candidate details and resume links on an application viewer screen.</li>
</ul>
<h3>3.1.3 Admin Module</h3>
<ul>
  <li><span class='bold'>FR-AD-1</span>: The system shall display total users, active jobs, and pending applications.</li>
  <li><span class='bold'>FR-AD-2</span>: The system shall allow the admin to block or unblock users.</li>
</ul>
<h2>3.2 Non-Functional Requirements</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>NFR-1 (Usability)</span>: The interface must load dark theme elements instantly based on the saved state, without causing white flashes.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>NFR-2 (Compatibility)</span>: The portal layout must fit mobile, tablet, and desktop screens with responsive margins.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>NFR-3 (Performance)</span>: The API response time for loading job results must be under 500ms under normal network conditions.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>NFR-4 (Security)</span>: Password credentials must be hashed using bcrypt before database storage.
  </li>
</ul>
<h2>3.3 Input/Output Requirements</h2>
<p>
  The input/output requirements define the data interfaces:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>User Credentials Input</span>: Email address, full name, secure password, and role selection (seeker/employer).
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>Job Details Input</span>: Job title, location, category selection, application deadline date, and text description.
  </li>
  <li>
    <span class='bold'>System Output Reports</span>: Structured active job list, recruiter candidates grid, PDF resume downloader, and admin dashboard charts.
  </li>
</ul>
<h2>3.4 Hardware & Software Requirements</h2>
<p>
  The development and runtime environments are specified below:
</p>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Environment Layer</th>
      <th>Development Specification</th>
      <th>Runtime Specification</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td class='bold'>Operating System</td>
      <td>Windows 11 / Linux (Ubuntu)</td>
      <td>Cloud Hosting (Node.js Environment)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class='bold'>Processor / RAM</td>
      <td>Intel Core i5 / 8GB RAM minimum</td>
      <td>1 vCPU / 1GB RAM minimum</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class='bold'>Database Server</td>
      <td>MongoDB Community Edition v7.0</td>
      <td>MongoDB Atlas Cloud instance</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class='bold'>Software / Runtime</td>
      <td>Node.js v20.20.2, npm v10</td>
      <td>NodeJS v20 Runtime</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class='bold'>Browser Client</td>
      <td>Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox</td>
      <td>Chrome, Edge, Safari, Firefox</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
